hical food" and "ethical eating" in socialist and formerly socialist societies. With essays by anthropologists, sociologists, and geographers, this politically nuanced volume offers insight into the origins of alternative food movements and their place in today's global economy. Collectively, the essays cover discourses on food and morality; the material and social practices surrounding production, trade, and consumption; and the political and economic power of social movements in Bulgaria, China, Cuba, Lithuania, Russia, and Vietnam. Scholars and students will gain important historical and anthropological perspective on how the dynamics of state-market-citizen relations continue to shape the ethical and moral frameworks guiding food practices around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aFood consumptionxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aFood consumptionxSocial aspects. 0aFoodxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aFoodxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aCaldwell, Melissa L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJung, Yuson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKlein, Jakob A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520958142423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520958142.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016